          "body": "God's response to the completed temple operates through what Old Testament scholars call 'name theology' (*shem* theology). God does not simply inhabit the temple physically; He consecrates it by placing His name there (9:3). His 'eyes and heart' will be on it perpetually — a relational, attentive presence, not a mechanical dwelling. This language echoes Solomon's own prayer in 1 Kings 8:29, where he asked God to 'attend to the prayer Your servant makes toward this place.' The answer of 9:3 is the divine acceptance of that request. The theological implication is profound: the temple's value is entirely derived from the name that inhabits it. When God threatens in 9:7 to 'cast the temple out of My sight,' He is not merely threatening a building — He is threatening to withdraw the name-presence that made the building sacred. The temple is only as holy as the God who condescends to dwell there, and His dwelling is covenantally conditioned."
