          "title": "The bilateral covenant — promise and warning interlocked",
          "body": "The covenant speech of 9:4-9 is the theological spine of the chapter and of the entire book of Kings. It is structured as a suzerainty treaty: the Great King (God) speaks to the vassal king (Solomon) and lays out the terms of the relationship — blessing for fidelity (9:4-5), curse for apostasy (9:6-9). The positive condition is precise: walk before God as David walked, 'in integrity of heart and uprightness' (9:4). The negative condition is equally precise: turn away from following God, fail to keep the commandments, and go after other gods (9:6). The consequences are catastrophic in both directions — dynasty established forever (9:5) on one side, Israel cut off from the land, the temple cast out, and the nation made a byword among nations (9:7) on the other. Reformed scholars (cf. John Calvin, *Commentaries on the Book of Kings*, on 9:4-9) rightly observe that the 'forever' of the Davidic promise (2 Samuel 7:16) is not revoked but channels through the conditional — the ultimate fulfillment of the Davidic covenant awaits the Son of David who walks in perfect integrity, namely Jesus Christ (Luke 1:32-33). The conditional does not make the covenant uncertain; it exposes the insufficiency of every Davidic son other than the last."
