          "title": "The predictive ruin — exile and the self-interpreting judgment",
          "body": "Verses 7-9 are among the most theologically dense in the entire Deuteronomistic History. God describes, in advance, the precise language future generations will use when they stand before the ruins of the temple and the desolated land. 'Everyone who passes by will be astonished and hiss and say, Why has the LORD done thus to this land and to this house?' (9:8). And the answer will be supplied not by a prophet but by the nations themselves: 'Because they forsook the LORD their God, who brought their fathers out of the land of Egypt, and adopted other gods' (9:9). This is theodicy built into the judgment itself. The ruins will be self-explaining; the exile will be self-interpreting. Jeremiah 22:8-9 nearly quotes this passage when describing the fall of Jerusalem. The ultimate fulfillment comes in 2 Kings 25:9-10, where the temple is burned and the walls of Jerusalem broken down — precisely what 9:7-9 anticipated. The chapter is not merely prediction; it is the hermeneutical key that tells the reader of Kings how to interpret every disaster that follows."
