          "title": "The worship note — sacrifice amid empire",
          "body": "Verse 25 is easy to overlook in the catalog of commercial and military activity that surrounds it: 'Three times in a year Solomon offered burnt offerings and peace offerings on the altar which he built to the LORD.' The three annual festivals — Passover, Pentecost, and Tabernacles — are Deuteronomy 16:16's prescribed calendar for all Israel. Solomon observes them. He burns incense before the LORD; he completes the temple's liturgical commissioning. The verse is not ironic; Solomon is genuinely fulfilling his priestly duties as covenant king. But its placement between Pharaoh's daughter's relocation (9:24) and the Ophir gold fleet (9:26-28) creates the chapter's sharpest pastoral tension: it is possible to maintain a complete worship calendar while simultaneously accumulating the precise categories of wealth and foreign entanglement that Deuteronomy forbids. Formal worship and covenant drift are not mutually exclusive. The chapter ends not with apostasy but with gold — 420 talents of it — leaving the reader at the edge of the precipice that chapter 11 will describe."
