        "title": "The second appearance — God re-frames the completed work",
        "range": "9:1-3",
        "excerpt": "The LORD appeared to Solomon a second time, as He had appeared to him at Gibeon.",
        "body": "The chapter's opening three verses accomplish a single theological move: they place Solomon's completed achievement back inside a divine frame. The narrator's 'now it came about when Solomon had finished' (9:1) is a temporal marker that signals a narrative turning point — this is a common device in the Deuteronomistic History (cf. Joshua 1:1, 'after the death of Moses'). The completion of both the temple and the palace, and 'all that Solomon desired to do,' marks the high point of the reign. At that precise moment God intervenes.\n\nThe reference to Gibeon (9:2) is the interpretive hinge. At Gibeon (1 Kings 3:4-5), God appeared to Solomon at the beginning of his reign and gave him the opportunity to ask for anything. Solomon asked for wisdom; God gave wisdom and added wealth, honor, and long life. The second appearance forms a literary inclusio around the whole of Solomon's building enterprise — the reign that began with God's generosity ends with God's condition. The entire narrative of chapters 3-8 exists between these two divine appearances.\n\nGod's response to the completed temple moves through three registers in verse 3: He has heard the prayer (responsive to Solomon's specific petition of 1 Kings 8); He has consecrated the house by placing His name there (an act of divine self-investment); and His eyes and heart will be there perpetually (an ongoing covenantal attentiveness). The 'name theology' here — God's presence mediated through His name rather than through localized dwelling — is the canonical middle ground between the transcendent God who cannot be contained in a house (1 Kings 8:27) and the particular God who chooses particular places (Deuteronomy 12:11). Solomon built the structure; God alone can make it a temple.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shem* (name) in 9:3 is the same term used throughout Deuteronomy 12 for 'the place where I will cause My name to dwell' — the Deuteronomic theology of divine presence. *Ayin* (eyes) and *lev* (heart) together denote the full personal engagement of God — cognitive attentiveness and affective commitment. *Kol-hayamim* ('all the days,' rendered 'perpetually' in NASB) is the same phrase used in Deuteronomy for the duration of Israel's covenant obligations."
