        "body": "The transition from the covenant speech (9:1-9) to the building catalog (9:10-28) is abrupt, and the abruptness is intentional. God has just articulated the terms of the covenant; the narrator immediately begins documenting how Solomon's imperial enterprise measures against them.\n\nThe Hiram transaction (9:10-14) is the first item in the catalog, and it is a quietly devastating detail. Solomon cedes twenty Israelite cities in Galilee to Hiram of Tyre in payment for cedar, cypress, and gold (9:11). The covenant land — the Abrahamic inheritance God promised Israel — is being used as currency in an international commercial transaction. Hiram comes to see his new acquisition and is unimpressed: 'What are these cities, my brother?' The nickname 'Cabul' (a Hebrew pun meaning 'worthless' or 'like nothing') is Hiram's verdict on the deal — and, by implication, a verdict on Solomon's fiscal management of the covenant inheritance.\n\nThe irony of verse 14 is sharp: Hiram sends Solomon 120 talents of gold. Solomon has ceded land to get gold. This is the beginning of the pattern Deuteronomy 17:17 warned against — the king who 'greatly multiplies silver and gold for himself.' The transaction is not condemned by the narrator; it is simply reported. But placed immediately after God's covenant speech, the reader is equipped to make the evaluation.\n\nChuck Swindoll (in his Kings commentary) observes that Solomon's cession of Galilean territory is an early instance of what becomes a consistent pattern: the king trading covenant possessions for commercial advantage. The land is God's gift (9:7 — 'the land which I have given them'); for Solomon to trade it is to treat the divine gift as a negotiable asset.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kavul* (Cabul, 9:13) is the place-name that encodes the commercial disappointment — its etymology is disputed, but the ancient readers understood it as 'like nothing,' 'worthless.' The narrator's 'to this day' (*ad hayom hazeh*) is his editorial signature, marking a detail that has persisted into his own time."
